I learnt the following about R-squared from the internet today: R-squared is the percentage of the dependent variable variation that a linear model explains. 100% represents a model that explains all of the variation in the response variable around its mean. Adjusted R-squared provides the same information as R-squared but adjusts for the number of terms in the model. Plot command makes the following diagnostic plots and par command puts them on the same page.

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(SS, which = c(1,2,5))
E <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = AA)
par(mfrow = c(2,2))

plot(E, which = c(1,2,5))

Q-Q plot shows that both genders have same distribution.

Residuals Vs fitted: Residuals = Observed value Fitted value. Y-axis= residual, X-axis= fitted values. Unwanted patterns of this plot = we cant trust the test. The shouldt be patterns. You shouldnt be able to predict the residual with fitted value, if the data is truly random.

Residuals vs leverage: can also be used to detect heteroskedasticity and non-linearity. Second, points with high leverage may be influential: that is, deleting them would change the model a lot. Points outside Cooks distance have high influence.

Now there are few points outside Cooks distance, that could affect leverage and the model.

Logistic regression for factors relating to higher alcohol consumption.I choose to use sex, absences,failures and address. My hypothesis: alco, absences and failures are related. Alco, sex and address are not related.

m <- glm(high_use ~ failures + absences + sex + address, data = AA, family = "binomial")

Extracting coefficients and then intrepeting them ass Odds rations And computing confidence intervals

OR <- coef(m) %>% exp CI <- confint(m) %>% exp

Printing Odds Rations and confidence intrevals

cbind(OR, CI)

This is also my answer to question number 5 (logistic regression and its interpretation) I would intepret the results as: Sex is the most related to high use, then failures, absences and adress = the further OR from zero, the more relation there is.

New model for the predictions. Sex, absences and failures are inlcuded variables, since OR > 1.0.

X <- glm(high_use ~ failures + absences + sex, data = AA, family = "binomial")

Predicting the probability of high_use

probabilities <- predict(X, type = "response")

Adding the predicted probalities to data AA

AA <- mutate(AA, probability = probabilities)

Using the probabilities to predict high_use

AA <- mutate(AA, prediction = probability > 0.5)

Making Crosstabulation of the target variable vs predictions

table(high_use = AA$high_use, prediction = AA$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   258   12
##    TRUE     86   26

Plotting the same results

g <- ggplot(AA, aes(x = probability, y = high_use, col = prediction))
g + geom_point()

As seen in both, the crosstabs and the plot. Lot of FALSE predictions were infact TRUE. FALSE predictions were more accurate since only 12 real FALSEs were predicted as high use. Sensitivity 26/112 * 100 = 23% and Specifity 258/270 *100 = 96%. Meaning the model is not good in predicting high alcohol use.

Bonus 10-fold cross-validation Define a loss function (average prediction error)

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

The average number of wrong predictions in the data

loss_func(class = AA$high_use, prob = AA$probability)
## [1] 0.2565445

K-fold cross-validation

library(boot)
CS <- cv.glm(data = AA, cost = loss_func, glmfit = X, K = 10)

Average number of wrong predictions in the cross validation

CS$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2591623

test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]
correct_classes <- test$crime
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)
  1. Linear Discriminant analysis on the train set, changing to numeric values and drawing a plot
lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "orange", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)
